      "content": "To achieve a dark and flavorful crust, you'll want to focus on increasing the Maillard reaction rate and intensity. Adding more sugar can indeed enhance the reaction, but be careful not to overdo it, as excessive sugar can lead to an overly sweet crust.\n\nAdjusting the pH can also impact the Maillard reaction, as a more acidic environment can slow down the reaction. However, a very acidic environment can also lead to over-browning, so it's a delicate balance.\n\nBaking soda, on the other hand, can actually inhibit the Maillard reaction. This is because baking soda is a base, and bases can neutralize the acidic compounds that are necessary for the Maillard reaction to occur. So, if you're looking to enhance the Maillard reaction, it's best to avoid using baking soda.\n\nA honey wash, however, can be a game-changer. The sugars in honey can caramelize and react with the amino acids in the dough, leading to a more intense Maillard reaction. The acidity in honey can also help to balance out the pH and enhance the reaction. A thin, even application of honey can add a rich, caramel-like flavor to the crust.\n\nIn terms of specific amounts, a small amount of honey",
